snippet.textDisplay:
I feel like this movie was the best it could have been.
Everything bad in this movie is a direct result of the Rian Johnson screw up. Because of him the first 45 minutes had to be a SW ep 8.5 to give them any chance at a plot.
Snoke was clearly going to be the main villain and probably Darth Plagueis, but after what Rian did they had to fix it somehow as Kylo in no way is a big bad type of character.

Things I liked:
- Rey actually got explained training. Remember in TLJ in that throne room fight she had still literally only had 5 mins of training yet was fighting like she had 10 years experience.
- No unlikable characters. Rose who I hated in TLJ got 2 mins of screen time, yay. There were no silly admirals with purple hair making stupid decisions in the most boring chase scene put to cinema.
- I really like Richard E Grant as the new General, fantastic portrayal and probably the best imperial officer since Tarkin. Even Hux was alright in the movie, great laugh moment at you know when.
- When you just let your fanboy come out there are really cool moments. I loved the huge Sith statues and the whole feel of that place. Also when Rey first shot the force lightning that made me really hyped.

All in all it's a good popcorn flick that did the best it could, considering the branching and most important movie of the trilogy is one of the worst films I've ever had to sit through.

I'd probably rank this as the rest of this trilogy and maybe above episodes 1 and 2, but not much better.

snippet.textDisplay:
#1 Don't change writers from movie to movie allowing them to do whatever the fuck they want with it. Hire one good writer, or perhaps a group of writers with one good lead writer to write the whole trilogy. Disney needs a master storyteller to fill the shoes of Lucas. The story of this trilogy has been chaotic, all over the board.
#2 Don't run movie productions like a political campaign. Stop trying to appeal to new demographics by sacrificing your substantial and established demographic. If you want to attract more female geeks, guess what, you already had ALL the female geeks there are. Creating an overpowered Mary Sue like Rey isn't going to suddenly bring in the "Sex and the City" audience to watch Star Wars. I get it. Women make up a big demographic, and trying to market to them makes sense. But don't sacrifice your current audience to do it. Besides, I think you already had your female fans and they didn't need or want an overpowered Mary Sue to make them like your franchise more.
#3 Read the treasure-trove of books and scripts that already exist. Don't just shove them in the bin. There really is an already established mythos for Star Wars. It's HUGE, there's lots of material. You didn't need to try to invent a new mythos.
#4 Step back for a decade before you try something like this again. You screwed up. Acknowledge that, make the staffing changes you need to make by sacking those responsible, and hire some good ones. Maybe reboot the final trilogy in 2029 using Lucas's script as the backbone. Hopefully, by then, CGI is good enough to bring in the characters we loved and do it right.
#5 NEVER BLAME YOUR FANS FOR YOUR FAILURE. That seems to be done quite a lot in Hollywood today. It's not smart. It means you've insulated your bubble so thoroughly you've lost touch with your fanbase. Listen to your CUSTOMERS.

snippet.textDisplay:
This is amazing and truly FASCINATING for me to witness. I have no leg in this conversation because I’m not a Star Wars mega fan(seen all of them maybe twice. Enjoyed them enough but don’t really care.) BUT as a DC fan and a fan of the DCEU, the last Jedi era online felt a lot similar to BvS online era in the LOVE!!!!! Or HATE!!!! war where you had to pick a side and no grey area discussion. Now this era has felt like Justice League where the studio went reactionary and changed the course mid way to appease LOUD hate and cries to ultimately go for the safest route and got a good but safe director to “fix” their big movie. I’m talking about JOSSTICE League.

Now thats a little different when you go into detail in a sense to where the DC movie was finished but the studio FIRED him, then brought a safe guy to completely copy the competition in a small amount of time with studios notes out the ass, but it blew up in their face. This Star Wars 3rd movie had its entire production from day 1 to “get it right” or “course correct” but it looks like they STILL dropped the ball for both sides. Very similar to my DCEU experience because what JOSStice League did was split the fandom that was already split. People who wanted “their” version of Superman, Batman, Lois, Lex, brighter tone, jokes, 10 solo movies before a big team up (because that’s apparently the only way ensemble films work totally contradicting the history of films with multiple characters you care about in the first movie) ect ...THEY didn’t get what they wanted. At the same time, people who LOVE, liked, or atleast appreciated Zack Snyder’s vision, tone, change from MCU’s formula, alternative take on the characters, and more modern and less nostalgic path got totally betrayed and hated it aswell.

Again this is so fascinating to view from the outside looking in. Man of Steel and BvS: Ultimate Cut are my personal 2 favorite DCEU films so far for some of the same reasons Coy said he wanted from Star Wars saga but at the same time he sounds like the type of guy who would dislike those films because it betrays what HE believes comic book films represent so iunno. I just know 2016 was my “Last Jedi” war and 2017 seemed to be my “Rise of Skywalker” war. Only difference is Last Jedi fans wont get a Snyder Cut era because this last film was planned from jump and there is literally NO other take unlike The Snyder Cut. I guess I’m just happy that I’m not the one emotionally screaming, defending, bullying, being bullied, betrayed, watching YouTube and the internet fight this year. Contrary to what most people think the Snyder Cut movement is. Lol But have at it y’all. I’m just an observer this year.
